caption: Excellent restaurant, friendly staff and clean place.

🇱🇷 🌲 ⛄ Happy 🌳 🐁  🐀 🌲 Chinese 🌲 🐀 🐁🌳 New Year 🌳  🐀   🐁  4718.   🇱🇷🗽🇺🇸  Downtown Yummy Restaurant located at 39 East Broadway is a nice Chinese restaurant that serves Cantonese cuisine.  The restaurant is located on the 2nd floor, and the stairs are quite steep. They do have an elevator to accommodate the elderly and the handicap, but you will have to go inside 39 - 41 East Broadway to access the elevator.  The place is neat, clean, tidy and well lite.  The staff is  friendly,   professional and attentive, all with a smile.  The food fresh and properly  prepared.  A place i would love to call my home cooked meals out.  Do enjoy.

Pretty noisy.  Elderly folks may need help getting up the stairs. There is an elevator as an option.  Food is good.  Comes out fresh.  We came here during the middle of the week at noon.  Some of the dishes were gone before we could even ask for them.

I like the way they stock the dim sum carts. Lots of variety on one cart. It also keeps the food fresher because it seems like they stock as the kitchen produces. It's not needlessly large or fancy. If you want Instagram fodder, go to Golden Unicorn. In my mind, this place has replaced a few dim sum spots I went to that now seen to have because bland and limited in the types of dim sum. I've only been once, but I'm going to keep coming back.

Authentic taste, good price especially for weekday lunch time, but I am really annoyed by the service. I always go there along for a quick lunch so ordering two dishes are just enough for me which only cost 5.5 (7.5 after tea and tips). They speak Cantonese which I can understand but I always speak mandarin in response. I don’t know maybe some point in me make them dislike me or something or I’m just overthinking, every time after I ordered, everyone just keep come and ask me do you want this or that...after me saying no they just leave an annoyed face to me and go away. And they are always WAY TOO FAST at taking your “empty” dishes away, which was SUPER ANNOYING. I feel like they only do this to me, maybe punishing me ordering too little or speaks mandarin. Sometimes there’s still some my favorite taro in the dish when I just picked and took a bite on that last piece of meat. And they will take the dish and turn away IMMEDIATELY, too fast that I couldn’t have say NO.  This time I just picked up a large piece of tofu roll when they IMMEDIATELY took the plate away.  Then my roll have no where to rest because it’s too big to eat in one bite. And although they usually are pretty fast at check which I like, today I already put money on the desk and everyone walk pass me and pretend not seeing me. Really arrogant service. Difficult to communicate. And when I was walking in alone, their female manager keeps staring at me like I’m a weirdo.  Feel like being discriminated because I wasn’t speaking Cantonese. I was so darn angry with the service.
Having just come from HK, this is one of the best dim sum places in NYC comparably. Excellent price too.

We went there for a reunion. All 20 people loved their Dim Sum items and noodles. Very inexpensive. This restaurant is our new favorite place. We will definitely visit again.

Great restaurants staff don't speak much English but are super friendly. The food is authentic, tastes and  with comunial tables the company is as interesting as the dishes. Take a friend or two and go get a meal you want forget in a hurry 😉

Very authentic Dim Sum experience, fair prices and not super touristy ... like Jing Fong ... quality of the food is good, and you can usually find a table without a long wait ...
Great for groups. Very nice food!
Great food and great service for our banquet!
Good price. I like the food. Hot tea. The two of us were sat with 6 other guests at the same table. Pick what you like from the cart.

Classic dimsum place upstairs with the ladies pushing carts. Kind of small and crowded during popular times such as weekends and holidays- be prepared to share tables with other people.  Taste wise, I'd say it's pretty similar to other consume places. Price wise as well.  Service was nice, they kept our cold and hot water filled.  Definitely worth giving a try at least once
Their dim sum are super delicious.  However, their AC is really really bad.  It’s super hot especially if you are eating steam hot food.  Bring a fan with you!
try it you it you may like it😚😚😜
Great food and presentation skills. Celebrating a relatives birthday, so we had the place to ourselves in the basement equipped with Karaoke.

Really really really cheap dim sum. A size Large item is $3.85!!!!!!!!!!!! We got 6 dishes for $23.25 (with tax)  The pork bao is a bit small, but everything else sizing is on par with other places but like 1/2 price.  Quality and taste is good.

Good foods at very reasonable prices.

Enjoyed a great meal with our family for Chinese New Year's.  Every dish was well seasoned just right.  Glad to have found another very good family friendly restaurant.

The best and creative seafood ever! Dim Sum is excellent! Small venue but always crowded.

Great local place, go with my family and friends, unique dishes. They have typical Cantonese style food as well as unique dishes. Get the special taro fish dish, crispy garlic chicken, and lamb chops! Always my go-to esp for picky Chinese parents that have seen and eaten it all.
One of the best Dim Sums I've had in a long time! I Highly recommend!
Great food great price
Great Cantonese style restaurant for dim sum, dinner or banquet. Great prix fixe dinner specials and a la carte entrees.
Amazing Authentic Dim Sum!
Very good food! Thoroughly enjoyed our Chinese New year dinner here! Definitely recommend. The fried fish was really good as well as the Peking Pork chop! Hidden Gem!

Definitely my favorite dim sum place in Manhattan. It's loud and crowded and people share tables, but the quality of food here is great. We got shrimp steamed rice roll, shrimp dumplings, fried salted dumplings, rice wrapped in lotus leaf, BBQ pork pastries, and ribs. Everything was delicious, quality was excellent. Best part is, 6 dishes for $23 (including tax and tea)! Wow. I'll be back for sure, I love this place!
traditional Chinese food

This is the best dim sum restaurant in Chinatown now.
I’ve been to China a few times and eating at this restaurant in New York’s Chinatown reminded me a lot of the food I had in China. The service was excellent and the food was as well.

Great place for dim sum.

Food was pretty decent, as you'd expect from a restaurant in this neighborhood. The service was often confused, and seemed disoriented (i.e. which tables dishes go to). My biggest peeve was that they weren't changing our plates fast enough. Once the first dish comes out, the gates open, and your own plate gets cluttered quite quickly. For a "new" restaurant, the upholstery doesn't reflect it (gf comment). BYOB is welcome, of course.
